<subsection xml:id="subsec-area-of-a-parallelogram-and-rhombus">
    <title>Area of a parallelogram and rhombus</title>
    <p>
       <m>\textbf{Area of a parallelogram}</m> 
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def-parra">
        <statement>

            <p>
                A parallelogram is a quadrilateral whose opposite sides are equal and parallel. Which other quadrilateral has similar characteristics like these?
            </p>
            <p>
               ðŸ”¹ The area of a parallelogram is given by: <m>Base \times Height</m>:
            </p>
            
            



            <p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Rectangle is a type of parallelogram where all the angles are 90Â°
                    </p>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      All rectangles are parallelograms, but not all parallelograms are rectangles.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
            <md>
                <mrow>\text{Area of a parallelogram} = \amp \text{base} \times \text{height}</mrow>
                <mrow>= \amp bh </mrow>
            </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                ðŸ”¹ The area of a parallelogram given the base is 28cm and the height 8cm is:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{A} = \amp b \times h </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 28\text{cm} \times 8\text{cm}</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 224 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                </md>
             </p>
            <p>
            The figure below shows a parallelogram with base and height labeled. 
            </p>
            <image width="40%">
                <latex-image label="Parr1">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \draw [very thick,fill=yellow](2,4) coordinate (D)-- (0,0) coordinate (A)-- (6,0) coordinate (B);
                    \draw [very thick,fill=yellow](6,0) coordinate (B)-- (8,4) coordinate (C)-- (2,4) coordinate (D);
                    \node at (3,2){height(h)};
                    \node at (3,-0.5){base(b)};
                    \draw [dashed] (2,4) --(2,0);
                    \draw(2,0) coordinate (A)-- (2,0.5) coordinate (B)-- (2.5,0.5) coordinate (C)--  (2.5,0) coordinate(D)-- (2,0) coordinate (A);
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            
            </image>
        </statement>
    </definition>
    

