    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Area of a rhombus}</m>
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def-Rhombus">
        <statement>
            <p>
                A rhombus is a type of quadrilateral that is a special kind of parallelogram. The key characteristics of a rhombus are:
            </p>
        
            <p>
                <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                    Opposite sides are parallel.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                    All sides have equal length.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                    Opposite angles are equa and adjacent angles are supplementary (they add up to <m>180Â°</m>).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                    The diagonals of a rhombus bisect each other at right angles (90Â°), meaning they intersect at 
                    a right angle and divide each other into two equal parts.
                    </p>
                </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                Move the slide slowly as you whatch how the rhombus looks like.
            </p>
        
            <figure>
            <caption>A Rhombus.</caption>
            <interactive xml:id="geogebra-rhombus" platform="geogebra" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
            <slate xml:id="rhombus-figures" surface="geogebra" material="qaw6nhfy" aspect="1:1" />
            </interactive>
            </figure>
        </statement>
    </definition>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <m>\textbf{Materials Needed:}</m>
                
            </p>
            <p> Ruler, Protractor, Pencil, Graph paper, Scissors (optional) and String or thread (optional)
                </p>
                <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                               Draw a Rhombus Using a ruler, draw a quadrilateral with all sides equal in length. Make sure the opposite angles are equal. Label the vertices as A, B, C, D in order.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Measure the Sides using a ruler to confirm that all four sides are of equal length.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Measure the angles using a protractor to measure each of the interior angles. Observe: Opposite angles should be equal.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                             <p>
                                Draw the Diagonals:
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    Draw diagonal AC and diagonal BD.
                                </p>
                                    <p>
                                    Measure their lengths and angles at the intersection point.
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    Observe: Diagonals bisect each other at 90Â°, and they are not equal.
                                                               
                                
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Cut and Fold (Optional):
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Cut out the rhombus and fold it along both diagonals.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Observe the symmetry and how the diagonals act as lines of symmetry.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <image source="/Rhombus.jpeg">
                    <shortdescription>Rhombus</shortdescription>
                </image>
                </sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Discussion Questions}</m>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                What do you notice about the sides and angles of the rhombus?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                How do the diagonals interact with each other?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                What makes a rhombus different from a square or a general parallelogram?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>
    
    
    
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
    </p>
   
    <p>
        The formula for the area <m>A</m> of a rhombus can be given in two common ways:
    </p>
    <p>
        <ul>
        <li>
            <p>
            Using the diagonals: <me>A=\frac{1}{2}\times d_1 \times d_2</me>
            </p>
            <p>
            where:
            </p>
            <p>
            <m>d_1 </m>and <m>d_2</m> are the lengths of the two diagonals.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
            Using the base and height: <me>A= \text{base} \times \text{height}</me>
            </p>
            <p>
            Where the base is the length of any side (since all sides are equal) and the 
            height is the perpendicular distance between opposite sides.
            </p>
        </li>
        </ul>
    </p>


    <example>
        <statement>
        <p>
            Calculate the area of the figure given it's 
            diagonals are <m>6\,cm</m> and <m>8\,cm</m>.
        </p>
        <image width="50%">
        <latex-image label="Rhombus1">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                % Define the rhombus vertices
                \coordinate (A) at (0,3);
                \coordinate (B) at (3,0);
                \coordinate (C) at (0,-3);
                \coordinate (D) at (-3,0);
                % Draw the rhombus with thick pink outline
                \draw[very thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle;
            
                % Draw diagonals with dashed lines
                \draw[very thick,dashed] (A) -- (C);
                \draw[very thick,dashed] (B) -- (D);
            
                % Mark right angles at the intersection of diagonals
                \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                \coordinate (T) at (0,0);
                \draw[very thick] (O) ++(0.2,0) -- ++(0,0.2) -- ++(-0.2,0);
            
                \node[below right] at (O) {O};
                \node[above] at (1.5,0.1) {6 cm};
                \node[below right] at (0.2,-1.4) {8 cm};
            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
            
            
        </image>
        
        </statement>
        <solution>
        <p>
            Area of a rhombus <m>= \frac{1}{2}</m> short diagonals <m>\times</m> long diagonal.
        </p>
        <p>
            <md>
            <mrow> A=\amp \frac{1}{2}d_1 d_2</mrow>
            <mrow> A=\amp \frac{1}{2} (6 \times 8)cm^2 </mrow>
            <mrow> A=\amp 24 cm^2 </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        </solution>

    </example>
    
